		<header>
			
			<h1>Agriculture drives the Cameroon economy  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the latest WTO Trade Policy Review (TPR), agriculture in Cameroon “[continued] to drive the rest of the economy” during the period 2007–11. Agriculture grew by an average of 4% annually over the period, with cassava, maize, plantains and cocoa showing the strongest growth. Agriculture was the main source of exports after petroleum. Exports included cocoa, coffee, bananas, rubber, palm oil, pineapples, cotton and timber.&nbsp;</p><p>As a result of this growth, agriculture as a share of GDP rose from 19% in 2005 to 21.7% by 2010, bringing agriculture back to the position it occupied in 2000 (when it accounted for 20.5% of GDP. However, the TPR argues that much more could be expected from Cameroon’s agricultural sector, as it has “immense potential, not only in traditional areas such as food or timber, but also in areas such as medicine or cosmetics”. The review notes that the country is already diversifying into “cocoa tree nurseries, supplying seeds, and the production and export of cassava”, but maintains that much more could be achieved “if there was less red tape, costs were lower and fewer people were involved”. Although “many agricultural support organizations remain under the supervision of the public or semi-public sector”, the review considers that most are in need of reform. </p><p>In this context, the WTO report maintains that government policy has been relatively unimportant in supporting the recent growth, with the rural population in practice producing food crops “without any support from the state, usually using very few inputs, and endeavouring to carry out the initial processing”. Average fertiliser consumption is estimated at 6.7 tonnes per 1,000 hectares of arable land, which is low compared with the 16 tonnes used in Côte d’Ivoire, the 35 tonnes applied in Australia and the 148 tonnes utilised in France. </p><p>However, the low use of fertiliser (which is mainly imported) makes the sector more self-sufficient, with Cameroon being “one of the few countries in Africa that is close to achieving food security”. Nonetheless, imports of some foods are important as a result of changing consumer tastes. Cameroon has a “relatively high level of dependence on certain food imports, particularly rice and wheat, fish and oil, which together account for over 40% of the value of domestic food consumption.” </p><p>Cameroon has dispensed with some of the protection that the CEMAC common external tariff affords to agriculture, but mainly in relation to foods that are primarily imported. It has used derogations to remove, rice, wheat and fish (among others) from the CEMAC sensitive list. More substantial changes could be expected, some of them affecting agriculture, if the Economic Partnership Agreement with the EU (initialled in 2007 and signed in 2009) finally comes into force. To date, Cameroon “has officially requested the postponement of the dismantling of its tariffs”. Under the original timetable for tariff dismantling, Cameroon would have completed the first phase of tariff liberalisation in 2013, dealing with the least sensitive category of products. It would also have been well advanced on the progressive removal of tariffs in the second phase of tariff dismantling.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Cameroon, Congo, Gabon, Central African Republic and Chad’, 29 and 31 July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp385_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp385_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Cameroon, with its “immense potential” in agriculture, illustrates that food security for a country is not (usually) the same as food self-sufficiency. Consumers demand some foods that cannot be produced domestically (or cheaper imported products, such as frozen chicken parts rather than whole chickens); and domestic production requires some imported inputs, as does processing, and especially marketing (so that food can be moved from where it is grown to where it is consumed). So, for a country with Cameroon’s resources to be approaching food security is not enough: Cameroon needs to be producing a substantial surplus from the agricultural sector as a whole (including exports of cocoa, coffee, bananas and timber) to ensure not only sufficient quantities for domestic consumption but also the generation of foreign exchange needed to fund the import component of the food security achieved. &nbsp;</p><p>In the CEMAC context, while the experience of Cameroon highlights just what farmers can achieve in a country with ample agricultural resources if left to get on with production, it also shows that broader policy measures and support are needed if local farmers, processors and traders are to meet the needs of a distant urban population and generate a surplus sufficient to dynamise the whole economy. </p><p>According to the TPR of Cameroon, the government has taken prompt action to protect the population from the effects of the 2008 food crisis, but the effect of its stabilisation scheme has been criticised by some observers as “prejudicial to Cameroon’s agricultural system”. More generally, the TPR sees much work still to be done by the government to replace obstacles to agriculture with effective support measures.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
